55-year-old male presents at 1800 with substernal chest pressure radiating to jaw x 3 hours. He is currently homeless, staying at the downtown shelter, and has no primary care physician. He is uninsured and reports he has not taken his blood pressure or diabetes medications in over 2 months because he cannot afford them. History includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and 30 pack-year smoking history. He walked to the ED from the shelter — no personal transportation.

Vitals: BP 178/104, HR 94, SpO2 97%, temp 98.4. On exam, appears anxious but nontoxic. EKG at 1815 shows sinus rhythm, no ST changes, no prior available for comparison. Serial troponins: initial 0.04 at 1820 (borderline — normal <0.04), repeat 0.12 at 2020 (elevated), third 0.08 at 2220 (trending down). CBC: WBC 8.9, Hgb 13.2. BMP: glucose 312, creatinine 1.4, potassium 4.8. HbA1c point-of-care 11.2%. Chest X-ray unremarkable.

HEART Score components: history moderately suspicious, EKG non-diagnostic, age 55, risk factors (DM, HTN, smoking) — 3 risk factors present. Given aspirin 324mg PO, started heparin drip at 1845. Morphine 4mg IV at 1900 for ongoing pain — improved 7/10 to 3/10. Started IV insulin for glucose management.

Social work consulted for insurance enrollment, medication assistance programs, and shelter-based follow-up coordination. Case manager arranged post-discharge transportation to follow-up appointments.

Spoke with Dr. Singh, hospitalist, at 2230 — accepts for admission for NSTEMI workup and uncontrolled diabetes management.

Disposition: admit to telemetry.
